id=fig2d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2e" class="graphic" aria-label="Lymph node morphology (types I–VI) is based on the relationship of the cortex to the hilum. As the cortex progressively increases in thickness, the appearance of the hilum is affected accordingly, as depicted on the illustrations (left; a–f) and US images (right; a–f). (a) A type I node with an imperceptible cortex (solid arrows) and preserved hilum (dashed arrow) is benign, with a negative predictive value (NPV) of 100%. (b) A type II node with a thin (&lt;3 mm) cortex (solid arrows) and preserved hilum (dashed arrow) is benign, with an NPV of 100%. (c) A type III node with a diffuse hypoechoic cortex greater than or equal to than 3 mm (solid arrows) with preserved hilum (dashed arrow) may be malignant but is more often benign, with an NPV of 93%. This was presumed to be reactive benign cortical thickening owing to recent ipsilateral COVID-19 vaccination. (d) A type IV node with a generalized lobulated cortex (solid arrows) with hilum (dashed arrow) may be seen with benign or malignant nodes. The NPV is 89%. FNA biopsy should be targeted to the thickest portion of the cortex. FNA biopsy results confirmed metastatic carcinoma in this case. (e) A type V node with focal and/or eccentric hypoechoic cortical lobulation and effacement and/or displacement of the hilum (dashed arrow) is demonstrated in this metastatic node. The positive predictive value (PPV) of a type V node is 29%. (f) A type VI node with absent and/or replaced hilum is seen as a hypoechoic mass in this metastatic node. A replaced hilum is the most specific feature of malignancy. A PPV of 58%–97% has been reported for type VI nodes. "><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig2e.jpeg" height="989" width="1862" aria-labelledby="fig2e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2e</span>. Lymph node morphology (types I–VI) is based on the relationship of the cortex to the hilum. As the cortex progressively increases in thickness, the appearance of the hilum is affected accordingly, as depicted on the illustrations (left; <b>a–f</b>) and US images (right; <b>a–f</b>). <b>(a)</b> A type I node with an imperceptible cortex (solid arrows) and preserved hilum (dashed arrow) is benign, with a negative predictive value (NPV) of 100%. <b>(b)</b> A type II node with a thin (&lt;3 mm) cortex (solid arrows) and preserved hilum (dashed arrow) is benign, with an NPV of 100%. <b>(c)</b> A type III node with a diffuse hypoechoic cortex greater than or equal to than 3 mm (solid arrows) with preserved hilum (dashed arrow) may be malignant but is more often benign, with an NPV of 93%. This was presumed to be reactive benign cortical thickening owing to recent ipsilateral COVID-19 vaccination. <b>(d)</b> A type IV node with a generalized lobulated cortex (solid arrows) with hilum (dashed arrow) may be seen with benign or malignant nodes. The NPV is 89%. FNA biopsy should be targeted to the thickest portion of the cortex. FNA biopsy results confirmed metastatic carcinoma in this case. <b>(e)</b> A type V node with focal and/or eccentric hypoechoic cortical lobulation and effacement and/or displacement of the hilum (dashed arrow) is demonstrated in this metastatic node. The positive predictive value (PPV) of a type V node is 29%. <b>(f)</b> A type VI node with absent and/or replaced hilum is seen as a hypoechoic mass in this metastatic node. A replaced hilum is the most specific feature of malignancy. A PPV of 58%–97% has been reported for type VI nodes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig2e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2f" class="graphic" aria-label="Lymph node morphology (types I–VI) is based on the relationship of the cortex to the hilum. As the cortex progressively increases in thickness, the appearance of the hilum is affected accordingly, as depicted on the illustrations (left; a–f) and US images (right; a–f). (a) A type I node with an imperceptible cortex (solid arrows) and preserved hilum (dashed arrow) is benign, with a negative predictive value (NPV) of 100%. (b) A type II node with a thin (&lt;3 mm) cortex (solid arrows) and preserved hilum (dashed arrow) is benign, with an NPV of 100%. (c) A type III node with a diffuse hypoechoic cortex greater than or equal to than 3 mm (solid arrows) with preserved hilum (dashed arrow) may be malignant but is more often benign, with an NPV of 93%. This was presumed to be reactive benign cortical thickening owing to recent ipsilateral COVID-19 vaccination. (d) A type IV node with a generalized lobulated cortex (solid arrows) with hilum (dashed arrow) may be seen with benign or malignant nodes. The NPV is 89%. FNA biopsy should be targeted to the thickest portion of the cortex. FNA biopsy results confirmed metastatic carcinoma in this case. (e) A type V node with focal and/or eccentric hypoechoic cortical lobulation and effacement and/or displacement of the hilum (dashed arrow) is demonstrated in this metastatic node. The positive predictive value (PPV) of a type V node is 29%. (f) A type VI node with absent and/or replaced hilum is seen as a hypoechoic mass in this metastatic node. A replaced hilum is the most specific feature of malignancy. A PPV of 58%–97% has been reported for type VI nodes. "><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig2f.jpeg" height="989" width="1882" aria-labelledby="fig2f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2f</span>. Lymph node morphology (types I–VI) is based on the relationship of the cortex to the hilum. As the cortex progressively increases in thickness, the appearance of the hilum is affected accordingly, as depicted on the illustrations (left; <b>a–f</b>) and US images (right; <b>a–f</b>). <b>(a)</b> A type I node with an imperceptible cortex (solid arrows) and preserved hilum (dashed arrow) is benign, with a negative predictive value (NPV) of 100%. <b>(b)</b> A type II node with a thin (&lt;3 mm) cortex (solid arrows) and preserved hilum (dashed arrow) is benign, with an NPV of 100%. <b>(c)</b> A type III node with a diffuse hypoechoic cortex greater than or equal to than 3 mm (solid arrows) with preserved hilum (dashed arrow) may be malignant but is more often benign, with an NPV of 93%. This was presumed to be reactive benign cortical thickening owing to recent ipsilateral COVID-19 vaccination. <b>(d)</b> A type IV node with a generalized lobulated cortex (solid arrows) with hilum (dashed arrow) may be seen with benign or malignant nodes. The NPV is 89%. FNA biopsy should be targeted to the thickest portion of the cortex. FNA biopsy results confirmed metastatic carcinoma in this case. <b>(e)</b> A type V node with focal and/or eccentric hypoechoic cortical lobulation and effacement and/or displacement of the hilum (dashed arrow) is demonstrated in this metastatic node. The positive predictive value (PPV) of a type V node is 29%. <b>(f)</b> A type VI node with absent and/or replaced hilum is seen as a hypoechoic mass in this metastatic node. A replaced hilum is the most specific feature of malignancy. A PPV of 58%–97% has been reported for type VI nodes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig2f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic" aria-label="Power Doppler US image shows peripheral nonhilar blood flow (arrows) in this metastatic node. Nonhilar blood flow has moderate specificity for malignancy when combined with additional suspicious features."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig3.jpeg" height="1231" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Power Doppler US image shows peripheral nonhilar blood flow (arrows) in this metastatic node. Nonhilar blood flow has moderate specificity for malignancy when combined with additional suspicious features.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic" aria-label="Illustration (left) and US image (right) show a type VI node in a 36-year-old woman with BRCA1 mutation who presented with cT4dN3cM0 metastases. A representative hypoechoic interpectoral Rotter node is seen with spiculated margins and an echogenic halo (arrows), findings suggestive of extranodal extension."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig4.jpeg" height="1025" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Illustration (left) and US image (right) show a type VI node in a 36-year-old woman with <i>BRCA1</i> mutation who presented with cT4dN3cM0 metastases. A representative hypoechoic interpectoral Rotter node is seen with spiculated margins and an echogenic halo (arrows), findings suggestive of extranodal extension.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic" aria-label="US images in three patients show suspicious lymph nodes (types IV, V, and VI, respectively) that underwent percutaneous needle biopsy with benign results. (a) Palpable lump in the axilla in a 54-year-old woman with a history of remote ipsilateral breast cancer and recent significant trauma to the upper torso and arm. US image shows a node measuring 2.8 cm in length, with diffuse cortical thickening (solid arrows) and preserved hilum (dashed arrow), a type IV node. Core biopsy results confirmed benign necrotizing lymphadenitis. (b) US image of the contralateral axilla in a 56-year-old woman with a new breast cancer diagnosis shows a 2.4-cm node with focal eccentric cortical lobulation (solid arrow) but preserved hilum (dashed arrow), a type V node. Core biopsy results confirmed that it was benign, with lymphoid tissue present. (c) Palpable lump in the axilla in a 57-year-old woman with a history of ipsilateral breast cancer. US image shows a round hypoechoic node (arrow) with replaced hilum, a type VI node. FNA biopsy yielded benign results."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig5a.jpeg" height="954" width="1311" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. US images in three patients show suspicious lymph nodes (types IV, V, and VI, respectively) that underwent percutaneous needle biopsy with benign results. <b>(a)</b> Palpable lump in the axilla in a 54-year-old woman with a history of remote ipsilateral breast cancer and recent significant trauma to the upper torso and arm. US image shows a node measuring 2.8 cm in length, with diffuse cortical thickening (solid arrows) and preserved hilum (dashed arrow), a type IV node. Core biopsy results confirmed benign necrotizing lymphadenitis. <b>(b)</b> US image of the contralateral axilla in a 56-year-old woman with a new breast cancer diagnosis shows a 2.4-cm node with focal eccentric cortical lobulation (solid arrow) but preserved hilum (dashed arrow), a type V node. Core biopsy results confirmed that it was benign, with lymphoid tissue present. <b>(c)</b> Palpable lump in the axilla in a 57-year-old woman with a history of ipsilateral breast cancer. US image shows a round hypoechoic node (arrow) with replaced hilum, a type VI node. FNA biopsy yielded benign results.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic" aria-label="US images in three patients show suspicious lymph nodes (types IV, V, and VI, respectively) that underwent percutaneous needle biopsy with benign results. (a) Palpable lump in the axilla in a 54-year-old woman with a history of remote ipsilateral breast cancer and recent significant trauma to the upper torso and arm. US image shows a node measuring 2.8 cm in length, with diffuse cortical thickening (solid arrows) and preserved hilum (dashed arrow), a type IV node. Core biopsy results confirmed benign necrotizing lymphadenitis. (b) US image of the contralateral axilla in a 56-year-old woman with a new breast cancer diagnosis shows a 2.4-cm node with focal eccentric cortical lobulation (solid arrow) but preserved hilum (dashed arrow), a type V node. Core biopsy results confirmed that it was benign, with lymphoid tissue present. (c) Palpable lump in the axilla in a 57-year-old woman with a history of ipsilateral breast cancer. US image shows a round hypoechoic node (arrow) with replaced hilum, a type VI node. FNA biopsy yielded benign results."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig5b.jpeg" height="957" width="1301" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. US images in three patients show suspicious lymph nodes (types IV, V, and VI, respectively) that underwent percutaneous needle biopsy with benign results. <b>(a)</b> Palpable lump in the axilla in a 54-year-old woman with a history of remote ipsilateral breast cancer and recent significant trauma to the upper torso and arm. US image shows a node measuring 2.8 cm in length, with diffuse cortical thickening (solid arrows) and preserved hilum (dashed arrow), a type IV node. Core biopsy results confirmed benign necrotizing lymphadenitis. <b>(b)</b> US image of the contralateral axilla in a 56-year-old woman with a new breast cancer diagnosis shows a 2.4-cm node with focal eccentric cortical lobulation (solid arrow) but preserved hilum (dashed arrow), a type V node. Core biopsy results confirmed that it was benign, with lymphoid tissue present. <b>(c)</b> Palpable lump in the axilla in a 57-year-old woman with a history of ipsilateral breast cancer. US image shows a round hypoechoic node (arrow) with replaced hilum, a type VI node. FNA biopsy yielded benign results.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic" aria-label="US images in three patients show suspicious lymph nodes (types IV, V, and VI, respectively) that underwent percutaneous needle biopsy with benign results. (a) Palpable lump in the axilla in a 54-year-old woman with a history of remote ipsilateral breast cancer and recent significant trauma to the upper torso and arm. US image shows a node measuring 2.8 cm in length, with diffuse cortical thickening (solid arrows) and preserved hilum (dashed arrow), a type IV node. Core biopsy results confirmed benign necrotizing lymphadenitis. (b) US image of the contralateral axilla in a 56-year-old woman with a new breast cancer diagnosis shows a 2.4-cm node with focal eccentric cortical lobulation (solid arrow) but preserved hilum (dashed arrow), a type V node. Core biopsy results confirmed that it was benign, with lymphoid tissue present. (c) Palpable lump in the axilla in a 57-year-old woman with a history of ipsilateral breast cancer. US image shows a round hypoechoic node (arrow) with replaced hilum, a type VI node. FNA biopsy yielded benign results."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig5c.jpeg" height="957" width="1093" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. US images in three patients show suspicious lymph nodes (types IV, V, and VI, respectively) that underwent percutaneous needle biopsy with benign results. <b>(a)</b> Palpable lump in the axilla in a 54-year-old woman with a history of remote ipsilateral breast cancer and recent significant trauma to the upper torso and arm. US image shows a node measuring 2.8 cm in length, with diffuse cortical thickening (solid arrows) and preserved hilum (dashed arrow), a type IV node. Core biopsy results confirmed benign necrotizing lymphadenitis. <b>(b)</b> US image of the contralateral axilla in a 56-year-old woman with a new breast cancer diagnosis shows a 2.4-cm node with focal eccentric cortical lobulation (solid arrow) but preserved hilum (dashed arrow), a type V node. Core biopsy results confirmed that it was benign, with lymphoid tissue present. <b>(c)</b> Palpable lump in the axilla in a 57-year-old woman with a history of ipsilateral breast cancer. US image shows a round hypoechoic node (arrow) with replaced hilum, a type VI node. FNA biopsy yielded benign results.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic" aria-label="Anatomic regional nodal basins. The margins of the pectoralis minor muscle separate the axillary levels. Level I axillary nodes (blue nodes) are located inferior and lateral to the lateral border of the pectoralis minor muscle. Level II axillary nodes (dark green nodes) are located posterior to the pectoralis minor muscle and include interpectoral Rotter nodes. Level III axillary nodes (infraclavicular, light green nodes) are located superior and medial to the medial border of the pectoralis minor muscle. Supraclavicular nodes (yellow nodes) are located superior to the clavicle and lateral to the internal jugular vein and sternocleidomastoid muscle. Internal mammary nodes (purple nodes) are located along the parasternal intercostal spaces."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig6.jpeg" height="2560" width="2300" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. Anatomic regional nodal basins. The margins of the pectoralis minor muscle separate the axillary levels. Level I axillary nodes (blue nodes) are located inferior and lateral to the lateral border of the pectoralis minor muscle. Level II axillary nodes (dark green nodes) are located posterior to the pectoralis minor muscle and include interpectoral Rotter nodes. Level III axillary nodes (infraclavicular, light green nodes) are located superior and medial to the medial border of the pectoralis minor muscle. Supraclavicular nodes (yellow nodes) are located superior to the clavicle and lateral to the internal jugular vein and sternocleidomastoid muscle. Internal mammary nodes (purple nodes) are located along the parasternal intercostal spaces.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic" aria-label="Illustrations demonstrate the AJCC N classifications. The AJCC anatomic stage is based on tumor size (T), N classification, and the presence or absence of distant metastases. The N classification is defined by the anatomic location and number of metastatic nodes. Black nodes indicate metastases."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig7.jpeg" height="2974" width="3782" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. Illustrations demonstrate the AJCC N classifications. The AJCC anatomic stage is based on tumor size (T), N classification, and the presence or absence of distant metastases. The N classification is defined by the anatomic location and number of metastatic nodes. Black nodes indicate metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic" aria-label="Lymphoscintigraphic map in the anterior projection after injection of technetium 99m (99mTc)–labeled sulfur colloid shows dual lymphatic drainage to the axilla (black arrow) and the internal mammary region (red arrow). The internal mammary pathway is an independent drainage pathway seen in 11%–21% of lymphoscintigraphic mapping procedures. (Adapted and reprinted, with permission, from reference 22.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig8.jpeg" height="1391" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Lymphoscintigraphic map in the anterior projection after injection of technetium 99m (<sup>99m</sup>Tc)–labeled sulfur colloid shows dual lymphatic drainage to the axilla (black arrow) and the internal mammary region (red arrow). The internal mammary pathway is an independent drainage pathway seen in 11%–21% of lymphoscintigraphic mapping procedures. (Adapted and reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r22" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r22">22</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic" aria-label="Axial MR images before (a) and after (b) NST show resolution of a suspicious node and provide indirect evidence of node positivity without biopsy confirmation. Initial MR image before NST (a) shows an 11-mm enhancing oval mass (arrow) lateral to the internal mammary artery and vein, a finding suspicious for a metastatic node. The internal mammary (IM) node was not identified at US, and therefore no biopsy confirmation results were available. After NST (b), the node is no longer identified (arrow) owing to treatment response."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig9a.jpeg" height="1099" width="1573" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Axial MR images before <b>(a)</b> and after <b>(b)</b> NST show resolution of a suspicious node and provide indirect evidence of node positivity without biopsy confirmation. Initial MR image before NST <b>(a)</b> shows an 11-mm enhancing oval mass (arrow) lateral to the internal mammary artery and vein, a finding suspicious for a metastatic node. The internal mammary <i>(IM</i>) node was not identified at US, and therefore no biopsy confirmation results were available. After NST <b>(b)</b>, the node is no longer identified (arrow) owing to treatment response.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic" aria-label="Axial MR images before (a) and after (b) NST show resolution of a suspicious node and provide indirect evidence of node positivity without biopsy confirmation. Initial MR image before NST (a) shows an 11-mm enhancing oval mass (arrow) lateral to the internal mammary artery and vein, a finding suspicious for a metastatic node. The internal mammary (IM) node was not identified at US, and therefore no biopsy confirmation results were available. After NST (b), the node is no longer identified (arrow) owing to treatment response."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig9b.jpeg" height="1099" width="1576" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Axial MR images before <b>(a)</b> and after <b>(b)</b> NST show resolution of a suspicious node and provide indirect evidence of node positivity without biopsy confirmation. Initial MR image before NST <b>(a)</b> shows an 11-mm enhancing oval mass (arrow) lateral to the internal mammary artery and vein, a finding suspicious for a metastatic node. The internal mammary <i>(IM</i>) node was not identified at US, and therefore no biopsy confirmation results were available. After NST <b>(b)</b>, the node is no longer identified (arrow) owing to treatment response.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic" aria-label="Core biopsy performed with a spring-loaded 14-gauge Achieve (Cardinal Health) biopsy needle with the nonthrow open sampling notch technique. (a) Prefire US image shows a depressed echogenic line, indicating the opened sampling notch (arrowheads) within the cortex of the node. The tip of the needle (arrow) is also within the node. (b) Postfire US image shows a continuous line as the sampling notch (arrowheads) is now covered and closed. The tip of the needle (arrow) remains stationary and does not advance beyond the node."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig10a.jpeg" height="965" width="1314" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Core biopsy performed with a spring-loaded 14-gauge Achieve (Cardinal Health) biopsy needle with the nonthrow open sampling notch technique. <b>(a)</b> Prefire US image shows a depressed echogenic line, indicating the opened sampling notch (arrowheads) within the cortex of the node. The tip of the needle (arrow) is also within the node. <b>(b)</b> Postfire US image shows a continuous line as the sampling notch (arrowheads) is now covered and closed. The tip of the needle (arrow) remains stationary and does not advance beyond the node.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic" aria-label="Core biopsy performed with a spring-loaded 14-gauge Achieve (Cardinal Health) biopsy needle with the nonthrow open sampling notch technique. (a) Prefire US image shows a depressed echogenic line, indicating the opened sampling notch (arrowheads) within the cortex of the node. The tip of the needle (arrow) is also within the node. (b) Postfire US image shows a continuous line as the sampling notch (arrowheads) is now covered and closed. The tip of the needle (arrow) remains stationary and does not advance beyond the node."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig10b.jpeg" height="965" width="1336" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Core biopsy performed with a spring-loaded 14-gauge Achieve (Cardinal Health) biopsy needle with the nonthrow open sampling notch technique. <b>(a)</b> Prefire US image shows a depressed echogenic line, indicating the opened sampling notch (arrowheads) within the cortex of the node. The tip of the needle (arrow) is also within the node. <b>(b)</b> Postfire US image shows a continuous line as the sampling notch (arrowheads) is now covered and closed. The tip of the needle (arrow) remains stationary and does not advance beyond the node.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic" aria-label="Staging of grade 3 invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) in the right upper inner quadrant in a 62-year-old woman. CT images depict the spatial relationship of the suspicious nodes to the margins of the pectoralis minor muscle. US images depict the morphology of the suspicious nodes, and US is performed to guide percutaneous needle biopsy. (a) Axial CT image shows multiple nodes in levels I and II axilla. The level I axillary nodes (arrows) are lateral to the lateral margin of the pectoralis muscle. The level II nodes (circle) are posterior to the pectoralis minor muscle. The vertical lines delineate the margins of the pectoralis minor muscles. (b) US image shows a representative hypoechoic round node (dashed arrows) with replaced hilum, a type VI node, in the level I axilla. (c) Axial CT image shows a level III axillary node (arrow) medial to the medial margin of the pectoralis minor muscle (vertical lines). (d) US image shows the corresponding hypoechoic round node (arrow) medial to the pectoralis minor muscle. (e) Axial CT image shows the parasternal location of an enlarged internal mammary node in the first intercostal space (arrow). (f) US image shows the corresponding enlarged right first intercostal space internal mammary node (arrows). (g) Axial CT image shows a soft-tissue mass (circle) lateral to the sternocleidomastoid muscle and internal jugular vein. (h) Power Doppler US image of the supraclavicular node shows peripheral nonhilar blood flow (circle)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig11a.jpeg" height="1127" width="1570" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Staging of grade 3 invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) in the right upper inner quadrant in a 62-year-old woman. CT images depict the spatial relationship of the suspicious nodes to the margins of the pectoralis minor muscle. US images depict the morphology of the suspicious nodes, and US is performed to guide percutaneous needle biopsy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows multiple nodes in levels I and II axilla. The level I axillary nodes (arrows) are lateral to the lateral margin of the pectoralis muscle. The level II nodes (circle) are posterior to the pectoralis minor muscle. The vertical lines delineate the margins of the pectoralis minor muscles. <b>(b)</b> US image shows a representative hypoechoic round node (dashed arrows) with replaced hilum, a type VI node, in the level I axilla. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image shows a level III axillary node (arrow) medial to the medial margin of the pectoralis minor muscle (vertical lines). <b>(d)</b> US image shows the corresponding hypoechoic round node (arrow) medial to the pectoralis minor muscle. <b>(e)</b> Axial CT image shows the parasternal location of an enlarged internal mammary node in the first intercostal space (arrow). <b>(f)</b> US image shows the corresponding enlarged right first intercostal space internal mammary node (arrows). <b>(g)</b> Axial CT image shows a soft-tissue mass (circle) lateral to the sternocleidomastoid muscle and internal jugular vein. <b>(h)</b> Power Doppler US image of the supraclavicular node shows peripheral nonhilar blood flow (circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic" aria-label="Staging of grade 3 invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) in the right upper inner quadrant in a 62-year-old woman. CT images depict the spatial relationship of the suspicious nodes to the margins of the pectoralis minor muscle. US images depict the morphology of the suspicious nodes, and US is performed to guide percutaneous needle biopsy. (a) Axial CT image shows multiple nodes in levels I and II axilla. The level I axillary nodes (arrows) are lateral to the lateral margin of the pectoralis muscle. The level II nodes (circle) are posterior to the pectoralis minor muscle. The vertical lines delineate the margins of the pectoralis minor muscles. (b) US image shows a representative hypoechoic round node (dashed arrows) with replaced hilum, a type VI node, in the level I axilla. (c) Axial CT image shows a level III axillary node (arrow) medial to the medial margin of the pectoralis minor muscle (vertical lines). (d) US image shows the corresponding hypoechoic round node (arrow) medial to the pectoralis minor muscle. (e) Axial CT image shows the parasternal location of an enlarged internal mammary node in the first intercostal space (arrow). (f) US image shows the corresponding enlarged right first intercostal space internal mammary node (arrows). (g) Axial CT image shows a soft-tissue mass (circle) lateral to the sternocleidomastoid muscle and internal jugular vein. (h) Power Doppler US image of the supraclavicular node shows peripheral nonhilar blood flow (circle)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig11b.jpeg" height="1129" width="1069" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Staging of grade 3 invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) in the right upper inner quadrant in a 62-year-old woman. CT images depict the spatial relationship of the suspicious nodes to the margins of the pectoralis minor muscle. US images depict the morphology of the suspicious nodes, and US is performed to guide percutaneous needle biopsy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows multiple nodes in levels I and II axilla. The level I axillary nodes (arrows) are lateral to the lateral margin of the pectoralis muscle. The level II nodes (circle) are posterior to the pectoralis minor muscle. The vertical lines delineate the margins of the pectoralis minor muscles. <b>(b)</b> US image shows a representative hypoechoic round node (dashed arrows) with replaced hilum, a type VI node, in the level I axilla. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image shows a level III axillary node (arrow) medial to the medial margin of the pectoralis minor muscle (vertical lines). <b>(d)</b> US image shows the corresponding hypoechoic round node (arrow) medial to the pectoralis minor muscle. <b>(e)</b> Axial CT image shows the parasternal location of an enlarged internal mammary node in the first intercostal space (arrow). <b>(f)</b> US image shows the corresponding enlarged right first intercostal space internal mammary node (arrows). <b>(g)</b> Axial CT image shows a soft-tissue mass (circle) lateral to the sternocleidomastoid muscle and internal jugular vein. <b>(h)</b> Power Doppler US image of the supraclavicular node shows peripheral nonhilar blood flow (circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic" aria-label="Staging of grade 3 invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) in the right upper inner quadrant in a 62-year-old woman. CT images depict the spatial relationship of the suspicious nodes to the margins of the pectoralis minor muscle. US images depict the morphology of the suspicious nodes, and US is performed to guide percutaneous needle biopsy. (a) Axial CT image shows multiple nodes in levels I and II axilla. The level I axillary nodes (arrows) are lateral to the lateral margin of the pectoralis muscle. The level II nodes (circle) are posterior to the pectoralis minor muscle. The vertical lines delineate the margins of the pectoralis minor muscles. (b) US image shows a representative hypoechoic round node (dashed arrows) with replaced hilum, a type VI node, in the level I axilla. (c) Axial CT image shows a level III axillary node (arrow) medial to the medial margin of the pectoralis minor muscle (vertical lines). (d) US image shows the corresponding hypoechoic round node (arrow) medial to the pectoralis minor muscle. (e) Axial CT image shows the parasternal location of an enlarged internal mammary node in the first intercostal space (arrow). (f) US image shows the corresponding enlarged right first intercostal space internal mammary node (arrows). (g) Axial CT image shows a soft-tissue mass (circle) lateral to the sternocleidomastoid muscle and internal jugular vein. (h) Power Doppler US image of the supraclavicular node shows peripheral nonhilar blood flow (circle)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig11c.jpeg" height="887" width="1423" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Staging of grade 3 invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) in the right upper inner quadrant in a 62-year-old woman. CT images depict the spatial relationship of the suspicious nodes to the margins of the pectoralis minor muscle. US images depict the morphology of the suspicious nodes, and US is performed to guide percutaneous needle biopsy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows multiple nodes in levels I and II axilla. The level I axillary nodes (arrows) are lateral to the lateral margin of the pectoralis muscle. The level II nodes (circle) are posterior to the pectoralis minor muscle. The vertical lines delineate the margins of the pectoralis minor muscles. <b>(b)</b> US image shows a representative hypoechoic round node (dashed arrows) with replaced hilum, a type VI node, in the level I axilla. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image shows a level III axillary node (arrow) medial to the medial margin of the pectoralis minor muscle (vertical lines). <b>(d)</b> US image shows the corresponding hypoechoic round node (arrow) medial to the pectoralis minor muscle. <b>(e)</b> Axial CT image shows the parasternal location of an enlarged internal mammary node in the first intercostal space (arrow). <b>(f)</b> US image shows the corresponding enlarged right first intercostal space internal mammary node (arrows). <b>(g)</b> Axial CT image shows a soft-tissue mass (circle) lateral to the sternocleidomastoid muscle and internal jugular vein. <b>(h)</b> Power Doppler US image of the supraclavicular node shows peripheral nonhilar blood flow (circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11d" class="graphic" aria-label="Staging of grade 3 invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) in the right upper inner quadrant in a 62-year-old woman. CT images depict the spatial relationship of the suspicious nodes to the margins of the pectoralis minor muscle. US images depict the morphology of the suspicious nodes, and US is performed to guide percutaneous needle biopsy. (a) Axial CT image shows multiple nodes in levels I and II axilla. The level I axillary nodes (arrows) are lateral to the lateral margin of the pectoralis muscle. The level II nodes (circle) are posterior to the pectoralis minor muscle. The vertical lines delineate the margins of the pectoralis minor muscles. (b) US image shows a representative hypoechoic round node (dashed arrows) with replaced hilum, a type VI node, in the level I axilla. (c) Axial CT image shows a level III axillary node (arrow) medial to the medial margin of the pectoralis minor muscle (vertical lines). (d) US image shows the corresponding hypoechoic round node (arrow) medial to the pectoralis minor mus