e, in the level I axilla. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image shows a level III axillary node (arrow) medial to the medial margin of the pectoralis minor muscle (vertical lines). <b>(d)</b> US image shows the corresponding hypoechoic round node (arrow) medial to the pectoralis minor muscle. <b>(e)</b> Axial CT image shows the parasternal location of an enlarged internal mammary node in the first intercostal space (arrow). <b>(f)</b> US image shows the corresponding enlarged right first intercostal space internal mammary node (arrows). <b>(g)</b> Axial CT image shows a soft-tissue mass (circle) lateral to the sternocleidomastoid muscle and internal jugular vein. <b>(h)</b> Power Doppler US image of the supraclavicular node shows peripheral nonhilar blood flow (circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig11g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11h" class="graphic" aria-label="Staging of grade 3 invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) in the right upper inner quadrant in a 62-year-old woman. CT images depict the spatial relationship of the suspicious nodes to the margins of the pectoralis minor muscle. US images depict the morphology of the suspicious nodes, and US is performed to guide percutaneous needle biopsy. (a) Axial CT image shows multiple nodes in levels I and II axilla. The level I axillary nodes (arrows) are lateral to the lateral margin of the pectoralis muscle. The level II nodes (circle) are posterior to the pectoralis minor muscle. The vertical lines delineate the margins of the pectoralis minor muscles. (b) US image shows a representative hypoechoic round node (dashed arrows) with replaced hilum, a type VI node, in the level I axilla. (c) Axial CT image shows a level III axillary node (arrow) medial to the medial margin of the pectoralis minor muscle (vertical lines). (d) US image shows the corresponding hypoechoic round node (arrow) medial to the pectoralis minor muscle. (e) Axial CT image shows the parasternal location of an enlarged internal mammary node in the first intercostal space (arrow). (f) US image shows the corresponding enlarged right first intercostal space internal mammary node (arrows). (g) Axial CT image shows a soft-tissue mass (circle) lateral to the sternocleidomastoid muscle and internal jugular vein. (h) Power Doppler US image of the supraclavicular node shows peripheral nonhilar blood flow (circle)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig11h.jpeg" height="850" width="1182" aria-labelledby="fig11h" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11h</span>. Staging of grade 3 invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) in the right upper inner quadrant in a 62-year-old woman. CT images depict the spatial relationship of the suspicious nodes to the margins of the pectoralis minor muscle. US images depict the morphology of the suspicious nodes, and US is performed to guide percutaneous needle biopsy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows multiple nodes in levels I and II axilla. The level I axillary nodes (arrows) are lateral to the lateral margin of the pectoralis muscle. The level II nodes (circle) are posterior to the pectoralis minor muscle. The vertical lines delineate the margins of the pectoralis minor muscles. <b>(b)</b> US image shows a representative hypoechoic round node (dashed arrows) with replaced hilum, a type VI node, in the level I axilla. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image shows a level III axillary node (arrow) medial to the medial margin of the pectoralis minor muscle (vertical lines). <b>(d)</b> US image shows the corresponding hypoechoic round node (arrow) medial to the pectoralis minor muscle. <b>(e)</b> Axial CT image shows the parasternal location of an enlarged internal mammary node in the first intercostal space (arrow). <b>(f)</b> US image shows the corresponding enlarged right first intercostal space internal mammary node (arrows). <b>(g)</b> Axial CT image shows a soft-tissue mass (circle) lateral to the sternocleidomastoid muscle and internal jugular vein. <b>(h)</b> Power Doppler US image of the supraclavicular node shows peripheral nonhilar blood flow (circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig11h">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic" aria-label="IDC in a 67-year-old woman with a history of left triple-negative breast cancer and a 4-month history of right axillary swelling. (a) Mediolateral oblique mammogram shows a 3.2-cm oval mass with pleomorphic calcifications (arrows). (b) US image shows a lobulated heterogeneous mass with replaced hilum and internal echogenic foci (arrow) consistent with calcifications. The biopsy results confirmed right axillary IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig12a.jpeg" height="1659" width="1399" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. IDC in a 67-year-old woman with a history of left triple-negative breast cancer and a 4-month history of right axillary swelling. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral oblique mammogram shows a 3.2-cm oval mass with pleomorphic calcifications (arrows). <b>(b)</b> US image shows a lobulated heterogeneous mass with replaced hilum and internal echogenic foci (arrow) consistent with calcifications. The biopsy results confirmed right axillary IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic" aria-label="IDC in a 67-year-old woman with a history of left triple-negative breast cancer and a 4-month history of right axillary swelling. (a) Mediolateral oblique mammogram shows a 3.2-cm oval mass with pleomorphic calcifications (arrows). (b) US image shows a lobulated heterogeneous mass with replaced hilum and internal echogenic foci (arrow) consistent with calcifications. The biopsy results confirmed right axillary IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig12b.jpeg" height="937" width="1399" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. IDC in a 67-year-old woman with a history of left triple-negative breast cancer and a 4-month history of right axillary swelling. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral oblique mammogram shows a 3.2-cm oval mass with pleomorphic calcifications (arrows). <b>(b)</b> US image shows a lobulated heterogeneous mass with replaced hilum and internal echogenic foci (arrow) consistent with calcifications. The biopsy results confirmed right axillary IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic" aria-label="Nodal recurrence in a 28-year-old woman with a history of right IDC and mastectomy with axillary lymph node dissection (pN1) 1 year previously who presented with a palpable lump in the right infraclavicular region. (a) US image shows a 2.3-cm node with diffuse cortical thickening (arrow) corresponding to the palpable lump in the infraclavicular region. FNA biopsy results confirmed nodal recurrence. (b) Axial PET/CT image shows that the nodal recurrence is medial to the pectoralis minor muscle, consistent with a level III node (white arrow). Additional disease is present in the anterior mediastinum (blue arrow). (c) Axial PET/CT image obtained at a more superior level than b shows supraclavicular-region FDG activity (rectangle). (d) Axial PET/CT image obtained at a more inferior level than b shows hypermetabolism of glucose at the internal mammary region (circle) and thoracic vertebra (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig13a.jpeg" height="1201" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Nodal recurrence in a 28-year-old woman with a history of right IDC and mastectomy with axillary lymph node dissection (pN1) 1 year previously who presented with a palpable lump in the right infraclavicular region. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a 2.3-cm node with diffuse cortical thickening (arrow) corresponding to the palpable lump in the infraclavicular region. FNA biopsy results confirmed nodal recurrence. <b>(b)</b> Axial PET/CT image shows that the nodal recurrence is medial to the pectoralis minor muscle, consistent with a level III node (white arrow). Additional disease is present in the anterior mediastinum (blue arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained at a more superior level than <b>b</b> shows supraclavicular-region FDG activity (rectangle). <b>(d)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained at a more inferior level than <b>b</b> shows hypermetabolism of glucose at the internal mammary region (circle) and thoracic vertebra (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic" aria-label="Nodal recurrence in a 28-year-old woman with a history of right IDC and mastectomy with axillary lymph node dissection (pN1) 1 year previously who presented with a palpable lump in the right infraclavicular region. (a) US image shows a 2.3-cm node with diffuse cortical thickening (arrow) corresponding to the palpable lump in the infraclavicular region. FNA biopsy results confirmed nodal recurrence. (b) Axial PET/CT image shows that the nodal recurrence is medial to the pectoralis minor muscle, consistent with a level III node (white arrow). Additional disease is present in the anterior mediastinum (blue arrow). (c) Axial PET/CT image obtained at a more superior level than b shows supraclavicular-region FDG activity (rectangle). (d) Axial PET/CT image obtained at a more inferior level than b shows hypermetabolism of glucose at the internal mammary region (circle) and thoracic vertebra (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig13b.jpeg" height="1336" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Nodal recurrence in a 28-year-old woman with a history of right IDC and mastectomy with axillary lymph node dissection (pN1) 1 year previously who presented with a palpable lump in the right infraclavicular region. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a 2.3-cm node with diffuse cortical thickening (arrow) corresponding to the palpable lump in the infraclavicular region. FNA biopsy results confirmed nodal recurrence. <b>(b)</b> Axial PET/CT image shows that the nodal recurrence is medial to the pectoralis minor muscle, consistent with a level III node (white arrow). Additional disease is present in the anterior mediastinum (blue arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained at a more superior level than <b>b</b> shows supraclavicular-region FDG activity (rectangle). <b>(d)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained at a more inferior level than <b>b</b> shows hypermetabolism of glucose at the internal mammary region (circle) and thoracic vertebra (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic" aria-label="