nal mammary region (circle) and thoracic vertebra (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13d" class="graphic" aria-label="Nodal recurrence in a 28-year-old woman with a history of right IDC and mastectomy with axillary lymph node dissection (pN1) 1 year previously who presented with a palpable lump in the right infraclavicular region. (a) US image shows a 2.3-cm node with diffuse cortical thickening (arrow) corresponding to the palpable lump in the infraclavicular region. FNA biopsy results confirmed nodal recurrence. (b) Axial PET/CT image shows that the nodal recurrence is medial to the pectoralis minor muscle, consistent with a level III node (white arrow). Additional disease is present in the anterior mediastinum (blue arrow). (c) Axial PET/CT image obtained at a more superior level than b shows supraclavicular-region FDG activity (rectangle). (d) Axial PET/CT image obtained at a more inferior level than b shows hypermetabolism of glucose at the internal mammary region (circle) and thoracic vertebra (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig13d.jpeg" height="1336" width="1178" aria-labelledby="fig13d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13d</span>. Nodal recurrence in a 28-year-old woman with a history of right IDC and mastectomy with axillary lymph node dissection (pN1) 1 year previously who presented with a palpable lump in the right infraclavicular region. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a 2.3-cm node with diffuse cortical thickening (arrow) corresponding to the palpable lump in the infraclavicular region. FNA biopsy results confirmed nodal recurrence. <b>(b)</b> Axial PET/CT image shows that the nodal recurrence is medial to the pectoralis minor muscle, consistent with a level III node (white arrow). Additional disease is present in the anterior mediastinum (blue arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained at a more superior level than <b>b</b> shows supraclavicular-region FDG activity (rectangle). <b>(d)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained at a more inferior level than <b>b</b> shows hypermetabolism of glucose at the internal mammary region (circle) and thoracic vertebra (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig13d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic" aria-label="Images show three different nonwire nonradioactive localization devices that are available for preoperative localization. The surgeon uses a handheld probe to detect the device intraoperatively. Left: The radar reflector (Savi SCOUT; Merit Medical) is 12 mm in total length, with a 4-mm body and a 4-mm nitinol antenna at each end. The reflector is deployed by retraction of the needle. Coin is included for scale. Middle: The magnetic seed marker (Magseed; Mammotome) is 5 mm in size and the smallest of the localization devices. It is end-deployed from the needle tip. The handheld probe magnetizes the seed. Right: The radiofrequency identification tag (LOCalizer; Hologic) is 9 mm in size and is made of a ferrite rod wrapped in copper. The unique identifier is read by the handheld probe, which is attached to a console. (Images adapted and reprinted, with permission, from Merit Medical [left], Mammotome [middle], and Hologic [right].)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig14.jpeg" height="880" width="2468" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Images show three different nonwire nonradioactive localization devices that are available for preoperative localization. The surgeon uses a handheld probe to detect the device intraoperatively. Left: The radar reflector (Savi SCOUT; Merit Medical) is 12 mm in total length, with a 4-mm body and a 4-mm nitinol antenna at each end. The reflector is deployed by retraction of the needle. Coin is included for scale. Middle: The magnetic seed marker (Magseed; Mammotome) is 5 mm in size and the smallest of the localization devices. It is end-deployed from the needle tip. The handheld probe magnetizes the seed. Right: The radiofrequency identification tag (LOCalizer; Hologic) is 9 mm in size and is made of a ferrite rod wrapped in copper. The unique identifier is read by the handheld probe, which is attached to a console. (Images adapted and reprinted, with permission, from Merit Medical [left], Mammotome [middle], and Hologic [right].)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic" aria-label="Specimen radiograph contents should reflect the findings depicted on a postlocalization mammogram. A larger clip is helpful to aid sonographic visualization in the event that the node appears normal after neoadjuvant treatment. In this case, a Tumark (Somatex Medical Technologies) U-shaped clip was used. (a) Specimen radiograph of an axillary specimen should demonstrate at least three items: the residual soft tissue corresponding to the lymph node (circle), the localization device (dashed arrow), and a marker clip (solid arrow). (b) Axillary view mammogram obtained after placement of the seed shows the residual node (circle), magnetic seed (dashed arrow), and a marker clip (solid arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig15a.jpeg" height="1247" width="1239" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Specimen radiograph contents should reflect the findings depicted on a postlocalization mammogram. A larger clip is helpful to aid sonographic visualization in the event that the node appears normal after neoadjuvant treatment. In this case, a Tumark (Somatex Medical Technologies) U-shaped clip was used. <b>(a)</b> Specimen radiograph of an axillary specimen should demonstrate at least three items: the residual soft tissue corresponding to the lymph node (circle), the localization device (dashed arrow), and a marker clip (solid arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axillary view mammogram obtained after placement of the seed shows the residual node (circle), magnetic seed (dashed arrow), and a marker clip (solid arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic" aria-label="Specimen radiograph contents should reflect the findings depicted on a postlocalization mammogram. A larger clip is helpful to aid sonographic visualization in the event that the node appears normal after neoadjuvant treatment. In this case, a Tumark (Somatex Medical Technologies) U-shaped clip was used. (a) Specimen radiograph of an axillary specimen should demonstrate at least three items: the residual soft tissue corresponding to the lymph node (circle), the localization device (dashed arrow), and a marker clip (solid arrow). (b) Axillary view mammogram obtained after placement of the seed shows the residual node (circle), magnetic seed (dashed arrow), and a marker clip (solid arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig15b.jpeg" height="1247" width="1010" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Specimen radiograph contents should reflect the findings depicted on a postlocalization mammogram. A larger clip is helpful to aid sonographic visualization in the event that the node appears normal after neoadjuvant treatment. In this case, a Tumark (Somatex Medical Technologies) U-shaped clip was used. <b>(a)</b> Specimen radiograph of an axillary specimen should demonstrate at least three items: the residual soft tissue corresponding to the lymph node (circle), the localization device (dashed arrow), and a marker clip (solid arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axillary view mammogram obtained after placement of the seed shows the residual node (circle), magnetic seed (dashed arrow), and a marker clip (solid arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic" aria-label="Flowchart demonstrates the multidisciplinary breast cancer treatment response based on imaging findings."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210053/asset/images/large/rg.2021210053fig16.jpeg" height="3125" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. Flowchart demonstrates the multidisciplinary breast cancer treatment response based on imaging findings.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210053&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Krishnamurthy S, Bevers T, Kuerer HM, Smith B, Yang WT. Paradigm Shifts in Breast Care Delivery: Impact of Imaging in a Multidisciplinary Environment. <em>AJR Am J Roentgenol</em> 2017;208(2):248–255.</div><div